body:
_off-topic, please ignore_

```cpp
if (cond) statement;
```
vs
```cpp
if (cond) {
    statement;
}
```

Putting everything on one line has 3 disadvantages:
1. It is not gdb friendly - it is not possible to set a breakpoint on `statement;` - to stop after `cond` and before `statement` (if `cond` was true).
2. It is not friendly to line-based code coverage - it will show that that line was executed even if `statement` was not.
3. It is not diff friendly:
3.1.
```diff
-if (cond) statement;
+if (cond) {
+    statement;
+    another;
+}
```
VS
```diff
 if (cond) {
     statement;
+    another;
 }
```
3.2.
```diff
-if (some || involved(123) || STUFF + here / 9 || you_have_to_check_if_this_is_the_same) woho(x * 19 - y);
+if (some || involved(123) || STUFF + here / 9 || you_have_to_check_if_this_is_the_same) woho(x * 29 - y);
```
VS
```diff
 if (some || involved(123) || STUFF + here / 9 || no_need_to_check_in_this_case) {
-    woho(x * 19 - y);
+    woho(x * 29 - y);
 }
```

